"(i) The evening air at Hither Hills State Park hung heavy with the scent of pine and damp earth, the sky a bruised indigo just beyond the reach of streetlights. Zoe pressed her palms against the cool glass of the park’s main pavilion, heart fluttering with a strange mix of nerves and anticipation as laughter and music drifted from inside. A crowd had gathered, their faces half-lit by neon string lights strung overhead, the hum of conversation a low tide beneath the rustle of distant leaves. Tonight was supposed to be a simple night of fun, but an odd tension threaded through the air like a shadow.\n\n(i) She stood near the edge of the makeshift stage, watching the band tune up their guitars and drums behind a stack of folding chairs. The air vibrated faintly with the thump of bass, the guitarist’s fingers dancing over frets as the crowd’s eyes flickered toward the sign-up sheet taped to the wall. Zoe’s name was there, scrawled in someone’s bold hand, but beneath it a note in blue ink: “Don’t be shy.” She wondered if it was a dare or an invitation, and for a moment, the music’s pulse seemed to slow, as if the park itself held its breath.\n\n(i) When her turn arrived, the lights dimmed, leaving only the glow of colored spotlights that painted her skin in shifting hues. She stepped onto the stage, the wooden planks cold beneath her feet, and the murmur of the crowd became a distant, muffled thing. Her voice, when it came, was steady but unfamiliar—like she was singing through a thin veil. Somewhere in the back, a woman in a red jacket watched her intently, eyes narrowed as if searching for something hidden in Zoe’s performance.\n\n(i) The band surged forward, guitars and drums locking into a tight rhythm that lifted Zoe’s song into something alive and urgent. She sang with more conviction than she expected, the lyrics blurring as the music swelled and the park seemed to close in around her. Between verses, she caught glimpses of faces in the audience—some smiling, some frowning,"